						<div class="verses">
									<div id="vers153582" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">1</div>
						<div class="vers-content">At that very moment, as Jeroboam stood at the altar and cast the incense down, a prophet came to Bethel, sent by the Lord from Juda;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153583" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">2</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and in the Lordâ€™s name he cried aloud against the altar, Listen, thou altar, listen to a message from the Lord. I see a prince that is to come, born of Davidâ€™s race, Josias by name, that shall sacrifice on thee the very priests who now feed thee with incense; the bones of dead men shall be thy sacrifice.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153584" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">3</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And he offered them proof, there and then; Here is a sign, he told them, to prove that this message comes from the Lord; see if this altar does not fall apart, and spill the ashes it holds!</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153585" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">4</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So cried the prophet against the altar at Bethel; and the king, hearing it, lifted his hand from the altar, pointed to the prophet and cried, Seize him! With that, his outstretched hand withered up; no more could he bring it back to his side;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153586" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">5</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and meanwhile, the altar fell apart, spilling its ashes; the very sign which the Lord had inspired his prophet to foretell.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153587" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">6</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Plead with the Lord thy God, the king said to him, and pray for me, that I may have the use of my hand again. So the prophet entreated Godâ€™s mercy for him, and his hand was restored to him, as sound as before.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153588" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">7</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And now the king would have the prophet come home with him to take food, and to be rewarded with gifts,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153589" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">8</div>
						<div class="vers-content">but he answered, Thou mightest offer me half thy kingdom before I would come with thee, before a crust of bread or a drop of water should pass my lips.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153590" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">9</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Such is the charge the Lordâ€™s word laid upon me; I must neither eat nor drink, nor go home by the way I came hither.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153591" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">10</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So he set out home by another road, not retracing the journey by which he had come to Bethel.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153592" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">11</div>
						<div class="vers-content">There was an old seer dwelling at Bethel, whose sons came and told him what deeds the prophet of God had done in the town that day; told what words had passed, too, between him and the king.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153593" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">12</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Whereupon their father asked what road he had taken, this prophet from Juda; and when he had found out this from his sons,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153594" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">13</div>
						<div class="vers-content">he bade them saddle the ass for him. Saddle it they did, and he mounted,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153595" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">14</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and went out in search of the prophet, whom he found sitting under an oak-tree. Asking whether he were the prophet from Juda, and learning that he was,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153596" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">15</div>
						<div class="vers-content">he bade him come home and share his meal.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153597" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">16</div>
						<div class="vers-content">But the other said, I must not turn back and go with thee, must not take food or drink here;</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153598" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">17</div>
						<div class="vers-content">when the Lord spoke to me, it was part of his message that I must neither eat nor drink at Bethel, nor leave it by the way I entered it.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153599" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">18</div>
						<div class="vers-content">But he would take no denial; I too, said he, am a prophet like thyself, and an angel has brought me a message from the Lord that I am to take thee home and give thee food and drink. With such words the prophet was beguiled,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153600" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">19</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and went back to eat and drink with him.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153601" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">20</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Even as they sat at table, the Lordâ€™s word came to the seer that had detained him.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153602" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">21</div>
						<div class="vers-content">A message from the Lord, cried he to the prophet from Juda. Thou hast disobeyed him; he, the Lord thy God, gave thee a strict injunction, and thou hast not kept it.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153603" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">22</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Thou hast turned back, there to eat and drink where he bade thee leave food and drink untasted. For thy punishment, thy body shall not be laid to rest in the burying-place of thy fathers.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153604" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">23</div>
						<div class="vers-content">When their meal was done, he saddled his own ass for the prophet, his guest.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153605" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">24</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And he, setting out on his journey, met with a lion, that slew him. There lay his body on the open road, with the ass close by; the lion, too, remained standing there beside its prey.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153606" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">25</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Passers-by told how they had seen it, a lion standing beside a dead manâ€™s body that lay in the road, when they reached the township where the old seer lived,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153607" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">26</div>
						<div class="vers-content">and when it come to his ears, he bethought him of his guest; It must be the prophet, said he, that was disobedient to the Lordâ€™s command; the Lord has suffered this lion to maul and kill him, in fulfilment of the divine threat that was made to him.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153608" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">27</div>
						<div class="vers-content">Then he bade his sons saddle him an ass; and when it was saddled,</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153609" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">28</div>
						<div class="vers-content">he set out on his journey, and found the body lying there by the road with ass and lion standing over it; never a morsel of its prey had the lion eaten, and to the ass it did no harm.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153610" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">29</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So the old seer took up the prophetâ€™s body and put it on the ass, and returned with it to his own city, to mourn over the dead.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153611" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">30</div>
						<div class="vers-content">In his own tomb he laid the corpse down, and they mourned for him, crying out, Alas, brother, alas the day!</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153612" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">31</div>
						<div class="vers-content">And after they had finished mourning, he said to his sons, When I die, bury me in this tomb where Godâ€™s prophet rests, laying my bones beside his.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153613" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">32</div>
						<div class="vers-content">It will come true past all doubt, the threat which he uttered in the Lordâ€™s name against the altar at Bethel, and the hill-shrines in the cities of Samaria.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153614" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">33</div>
						<div class="vers-content">All this notwithstanding, Jeroboam would not amend his sinful ways; still he appointed priests here and there and everywhere among the people, consecrating the first comer to minister at his hill-shrines.</div>
					</div>
									<div id="vers153615" class="vers">
												<div class="vers-no">34</div>
						<div class="vers-content">So it was that the race of Jeroboam became tainted with guilt, doomed to perish and to leave no trace behind it.<span class="content-paragraph"><br><br></span></div>
					</div>
							</div>
